    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Don't panic, as long as you are cutting away the circling roots, you are actually helping the plant, but be careful not to slice too deeply into the main structural roots. If you see roots that are brown, mushy, or have a foul odor, those are likely diseased and should be removed along with the circling ones. Healthy roots should be firm, white or light tan, and flexible rather than brittle. Since your fig is getting big, it will need more space, but remember that fiddle leaf figs are sensitive to shock, so handle the soil gently and avoid compacting it too much. If you are still worried, you can let the plant sit in its current pot for a few days while you prepare the new setup, just to give it a moment to adjust.",
